---
description: Implement every ready feature in the queue back-to-back in one unattended run (batch /next-feature).
---

Acting as the `leader`, drive the entire ready queue to `done` in one run. Process every <% if (it.isSdd) { %>`approved`<% } else { %>`pending`<% } %> feature whose `dependsOn` are all `done`, in dependency order, **strictly one at a time** — never more than one feature `in_progress`. This is the batch form of `/next-feature`: it only implements work that is already <% if (it.isSdd) { %>approved<% } else { %>queued<% } %>, and never brainstorms, writes specs, or asks discovery questions.

1. Run `<%= it.verifyCmd %>` to confirm a green starting state. If it is red, stop and report — never start a batch on a red tree.
2. Run `reins status` to build the dependency-ordered queue of features ready to implement. Present that ordered list to the human and **wait for a single go-ahead**. This is the only time autopilot pauses — once you have the OK, run to completion with no further questions.
3. Then, for each feature in order:
   1. Set it `in_progress`.<% if (it.isSdd) { %> Its spec is already human-approved — do **not** re-open discovery or ask anything.<% } %> Delegate to `implementer`, then `reviewer` (and `security-reviewer` if the change touches auth, input, IO, secrets, or dependencies; `design-reviewer` if it touches UI, components, styles, or copy). Iterate implementer ↔ reviewer until the reviewer approves.
   2. On approval, mark the feature `done`, then run `<%= it.verifyCmd %>` to confirm the tree is still green.
   3. **Halt on trouble.** If a feature ends up `blocked`, the reviewer keeps requesting changes that cannot be resolved, or `<%= it.verifyCmd %>` goes red, **stop the whole run**. Leave state coherent — no feature stuck `in_progress` — and report which features completed and which remain.
   4. Otherwise, move on to the next feature.
4. When the queue is drained (or you halted), run `<%= it.verifyCmd %>` once more and report a summary: features completed this run, features still queued, and any blocker that stopped you.

Remember: you orchestrate — subagents write their results to `progress/` (always in English) — and exactly one feature is `in_progress` at a time.
